TypeSignature.Value: .class public interface auto ansi abstract PageSetup

Docs.summary: Represents the page setup description. The object contains all page setup attributes (left margin, bottom margin, paper size, and so on) as properties.

remarks.para: Use the property of a or object to return a object.

remarks.para: This property applies only to chart sheets (it cannot be used with embedded charts).

MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property Creator As XlCreator

Docs.summary: Returns a 32-bit integer that indicates the application in which this object was created.

remarks.para: If the object was created in Microsoft Excel, this property returns the string XCEL, which is equivalent to the hexadecimal number 5843454C.
The Creator property is designed to be used in Microsoft Excel for the Macintosh, where each application has a four-character creator code. For example, Microsoft Excel has the creator code XCEL.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property bool DifferentFirstPageHeaderFooter { bool get(); void set(bool value); };

MemberSignature.Value: public: property bool Draft { bool get(); void set(bool value); };

Docs.summary: True if the sheet will be printed without graphics.

remarks.para: Setting this property to True makes printing faster (at the expense of not printing graphics).

MemberSignature.Value: public: property System::Object ^ FitToPagesTall { System::Object ^ get(); void set(System::Object ^ value); };

Docs.summary: Returns or sets the number of pages tall the worksheet will be scaled to when it's printed. Applies only to worksheets.

remarks.para: If this property is False, Microsoft Excel scales the worksheet according to the property.
If the property is True, the FitToPagesTall property is ignored.

remarks.para: If this property is False, Microsoft Excel scales the worksheet according to the property.
If the property is True, the FitToPagesWide property is ignored.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property Microsoft::Office::Interop::Excel::XlPageOrientation Orientation { Microsoft::Office::Interop::Excel::XlPageOrientation get(); void set(Microsoft::Office::Interop::Excel::XlPageOrientation value); };

Docs.summary: Portrait or landscape printing mode.

remarks.para: For OLAP data sources, setting this property for one field in a hierarchy sets the orientation for the other fields in the same hierarchy. Dimension fields can only be oriented in the row, column, and page field areas of the PivotTable report. Measure fields can only be oriented in the data area. Setting a hierarchy or data field to xlHidden removes the hierarchy or field from the PivotTable report.

MemberSignature.Value: public object PrintQuality[object Index] { get; set; }
Public Property PrintQuality(Optional Index As Object) As Object
public: property System::Object ^ PrintQuality[System::Object ^] { System::Object ^ get(System::Object ^ Index); void set(System::Object ^ Index, System::Object ^ value); };

Docs.param: Optional Object. Horizontal print quality (1) or vertical print quality (2). Some printers may not support vertical print quality. If you don’t specify this argument, the PrintQuality property returns (or can be set to) a two-element array that contains both horizontal and vertical print quality.
Docs.summary: Returns or sets the print quality.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property System::String ^ PrintTitleColumns { System::String ^ get(); void set(System::String ^ value); };

Docs.summary: Returns or sets the columns that contain the cells to be repeated on the left side of each page as a string in A1-style notation in the language of the macro.

remarks.para: If you specify only part of a column or columns, Microsoft Excel expands the range to full columns.
Set this property to False or to the empty string ("") to turn off title columns.
This property applies only to worksheet pages.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property System::String ^ PrintTitleRows { System::String ^ get(); void set(System::String ^ value); };

Docs.summary: Returns or sets the rows that contain the cells to be repeated at the top of each page as a string in A1-style notation in the language of the macro.

remarks.para: If you specify only part of a row or rows, Microsoft Excel expands the range to full rows.
Set this property to False or to the empty string ("") to turn off title rows.
This property applies only to worksheet pages.
